#compdef gql-iterate
# ============================================================================
# gql-iterate - Run a GraphQL query repeatedly with per-row variables from CSV
#                (Node, ?)
#
# Author : Georg Stadler (efstajas)
# Upstream: https://github.com/efstajas/gql-iterate
# npm    : @efstajas/gql-iterate (binary: gql-iterate)
#
# `gql-iterate` is a lightweight CLI for the "I have a CSV
# of inputs + a GraphQL query template, run it N times" use
# case. Read a CSV file with headers matching the GraphQL
# query's variable names, fire one GraphQL request per row
# (with concurrency limiter via bottleneck), and emit each
# JSON response one-per-line on stdout. Useful for bulk
# data export, mass mutations, or quick scripts against any
# GraphQL endpoint without writing TypeScript boilerplate.
#
# Usage:
#   gql-iterate --host <url> --input <csv> --query <gql> [options]
#
# Flags (yargs):
#   --host <url>             - GraphQL endpoint URL (REQUIRED)
#   --input <csv>            - CSV file path; column headers must
#                              match query variable names
#                              (REQUIRED)
#   --query <gql>            - GraphQL query file path with
#                              variable references like $id, $email
#                              (REQUIRED)
#   --bearer <token>         - optional Bearer token for the
#                              Authorization header
#   --concurrency <n>        - parallel request count
#                              (0 = fire all at once; default 0)
#   -h, --help               - print help
#   --version                - print version
#
# Example:
#   $ cat users.csv
#   id,email
#   1,alice@example.com
#   2,bob@example.com
#   $ cat update-email.gql
#   mutation UpdateEmail($id: ID!, $email: String!) {
#     updateUser(id: $id, email: $email) { id email }
#   }
#   $ gql-iterate --host https://api.example.com/graphql \
#                 --input users.csv --query update-email.gql \
#                 --bearer $TOKEN --concurrency 5
#
# The graphql-request lane is built on `graphql-request
# ^3.4.0` (declared verbatim at upstream package.json HEAD),
# the canonical minimal Node GraphQL client by Prisma Labs
# (later renamed graffle/graffle in 2024; package still
# published as `graphql-request` on npm). The library is
# the de-facto "I just want to send a GraphQL request from
# Node without ceremony" choice - ~5 million weekly
# downloads on npm. The API is a single async function:
# `client.request(query, variables)` returns a typed
# Promise resolving to the GraphQL response data. gql-
# iterate uses this minimal surface as the per-row request
# primitive.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 237 :: GraphQL clients (typed queries from .graphql files)  [CLOSES]
# Round 1411 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 237 (230th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : graphql-rust/graphql-client  [R1409 _arbor-cli]
#   Go      : Khan/genqlient               [R1410 _rggr]
#   TS/Node : prisma-labs/graphql-request  [R1411 THIS FILE]
#
# graphql-request rounds out Axis 237 with the *runtime-
# typed* end of the spectrum. The Rust + Go lanes both
# commit to compile-time-typed codegen (graphql-client's
# derive macro, genqlient's `go generate` step);
# graphql-request leaves typing to the user - either as
# `any` (untyped at runtime) or via TypeScript generics
# the user supplies at the call site.
#
# The structural commentary across Axis 237:
#   - graphql-client (Rust): compile-time codegen via
#     derive macro, zero runtime cost for typing
#   - genqlient (Go): build-time codegen committed to repo,
#     zero runtime cost for typing
#   - graphql-request (Node): runtime-typed via generics,
#     types defined by the caller; matching codegen
#     (graphql-codegen) ships separately
#
# The Node lane's pragmatic choice reflects the JS
# ecosystem's preference for opt-in tooling over baked-in
# codegen: many graphql-request users skip codegen entirely
# and use `any` + manual type definitions; the more
# rigorous users add graphql-codegen + GraphQL Code
# Generator to produce typed query hooks at build time.
# Both workflows are first-class.
#
# All three lanes produce wire-identical HTTP POST bodies
# for the same query + variables. The receiving GraphQL
# server cannot tell which client produced the request -
# the spec contract is total. What diverges is the
# producing-app's *type discipline*, not the wire format.
#
# Axis 237 closes at round 1411 - 230th axis closed total.
# ============================================================================

_gql-iterate() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--host[GraphQL endpoint URL]:url:' \
        '--input[CSV input file]:file:_files -g "*.csv"' \
        '--query[GraphQL query file]:file:_files -g "*.(gql|graphql)"' \
        '--bearer[Bearer token for Authorization header]:token:' \
        '--concurrency[parallel request count (0 = fire all at once)]:n:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]'
}

_gql-iterate "$@"
